{"key":"post-8744209","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8744209</id>\n<content>Toss them out.&amp;nbsp; They're contaminated with bacteria.&amp;nbsp; The tell-tale sign is the 'milky' appearance where the substrate is pushed against the glass.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Any way you mix the flour and verm is fine, as long as you get it well mixed.&amp;nbsp; With most preparations, I mix all the dry ingredients first, and then add moisture.&amp;nbsp; However, with brf cakes, the flour is so much finer than the verm, it tends to sink to the bottom of your bowl and not mix in well if you do it that way.&amp;nbsp; Roadkill, who did the pf tek demonstration on 'Let's Grow Mushrooms' uses the verm and water mix first, followed by slowly adding the rice flour.&amp;nbsp; His method definitely seems to work better for pf type cakes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, that isn't what caused your problem.&amp;nbsp; The bacteria was caused by exposure to bacteria after sterilization.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8744553</next>\n<prev>8743893</prev>\n<first>8743685</first>\n<last>8753172</last>\n<when>1218223833</when>\n<utime>08/08/08 10:30 PM</utime>\n</post>"}